servings: 2
---

Boil a full #kettle{}. Pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} with
@salt{1/4%tsp} on high heat. Add the @basmati rice{150%g} and @ground turmeric{1/2%tsp}
and cook for ~{10-12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the saucepan. Cover with a #lid{}
and leave to the side until ready to serve.

Halve, peel and slice the @red onion{1} as thinly as you can. Pop half the onion
into a #small bowl{} with the @cider vinegar{15%ml}, @sugar{1/2%tsp} and a pinch of
@salt{}. Toss to combine, then set aside to pickle.

Meanwhile, halve any thick @tenderstem broccoli{150%g} stems lengthways, then cut
widthways into thirds. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot,
add the @British beef mince{120%g}, broccoli and remaining onion. Fry until the
mince has browned and the veg has softened, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to
break up the mince as it cooks.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

When the mince has browned, drain and discard any excess fat, then season with
@salt{} and @black pepper{}. Sprinkle over the @korma curry paste{50%g},
@North Indian style spice mix{1} and garlic. Cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Stir the @water{150%ml} and @chicken stock paste{15%g} into the beef. Bring to the
boil, then lower the heat and simmer until slightly thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.
Season with salt and pepper. Stir the cooked rice through the sauce, mixing
together well so all the rice is coated. Remove from the heat, then stir through
the @mango chutney{40%g}.

Share your cheat's biriyani between your #bowls{}. Drizzle over the
@low fat natural yoghurt{75%g}, then top with the pickled onion to finish.
Enjoy!